    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks that makes sense. but you mentioned it's kind of like it's defying physics... i read somewhere that Einstein called it 'spooky action at a distance' because it felt so weird. can you explain why it's considered so spooky? like what's the actual mechanism that makes it feel that way?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Albert Einstein's infamous \"spooky action at a distance\" comment was due to the apparent non-locality of entanglement, which challenges classical notions of space and time. The mechanism behind this spookiness lies in the fact that, in an entangled system, the wave function of one particle is encoded in the wave function of the other, regardless of the distance between them.\n\nThis means that when you measure one particle, information about the other particle's state is \" downloaded\" into your measurement apparatus, instantly affecting the state of both particles. It's as if the information is transmitted or correlated in a way that appears to violate the fundamental limits of speed, yet the entangled correlation can persist even when the physical particles are separated by vast distances. This phenomenon has been experimentally confirmed and is a fundamental aspect of quantum mechanics.",
      "source": "target",
